{"name":"Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Covering.Vitali","instances":[],"imports":["Init","Mathlib.Topology.MetricSpace.Basic","Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Constructions.BorelSpace.Basic","Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Covering.VitaliFamily"],"declarations":[{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.lean#L405-L444","name":"Vitali.vitaliFamily","kind":"def","docLink":"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.html#Vitali.vitaliFamily","doc":"Assume that around every point there are arbitrarily small scales at which the measure is\ndoubling. Then the set of closed sets `a` with nonempty interior contained in `closedBall x r` and\ncovering a fixed proportion `1/C` of the ball `closedBall x (3 * r)` forms a Vitali family.\nThis is essentially a restatement of the measurable Vitali theorem. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.lean#L206-L398","name":"Vitali.exists_disjoint_covering_ae","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.html#Vitali.exists_disjoint_covering_ae","doc":"The measurable Vitali covering theorem. Assume one is given a family `t` of closed sets with\nnonempty interior, such that each `a ∈ t` is included in a ball `B (x, r)` and covers a definite\nproportion of the ball `B (x, 3 r)` for a given measure `μ` (think of the situation where `μ` is\na doubling measure and `t` is a family of balls). Consider a (possibly non-measurable) set `s`\nat which the family is fine, i.e., every point of `s` belongs to arbitrarily small elements of `t`.\nThen one can extract from `t` a disjoint subfamily that covers almost all `s`.\n\nFor more flexibility, we give a statement with a parameterized family of sets.\n"},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.lean#L165-L194","name":"Vitali.exists_disjoint_subfamily_covering_enlargment_closedBall","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.html#Vitali.exists_disjoint_subfamily_covering_enlargment_closedBall","doc":"Vitali covering theorem, closed balls version: given a family `t` of closed balls, one can\nextract a disjoint subfamily `u ⊆ t` so that all balls in `t` are covered by the 5-times\ndilations of balls in `u`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.lean#L62-L159","name":"Vitali.exists_disjoint_subfamily_covering_enlargment","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/MeasureTheory/Covering/Vitali.html#Vitali.exists_disjoint_subfamily_covering_enlargment","doc":"Vitali covering theorem: given a set `t` of subsets of a type, one may extract a disjoint\nsubfamily `u` such that the `τ`-enlargment of this family covers all elements of `t`, where `τ > 1`\nis any fixed number.\n\nWhen `t` is a family of balls, the `τ`-enlargment of `ball x r` is `ball x ((1+2τ) r)`. In general,\nit is expressed in terms of a function `δ` (think \"radius\" or \"diameter\"), positive and bounded on\nall elements of `t`. The condition is that every element `a` of `t` should intersect an\nelement `b` of `u` of size larger than that of `a` up to `τ`, i.e., `δ b ≥ δ a / τ`.\n\nWe state the lemma slightly more generally, with an indexed family of sets `B a` for `a ∈ t`, for\nwider applicability.\n"}]}